[[File:Stratos II+ at apogee.jpg|thumb|Stratos II+ sounding rocket launched from El Arenosillo.]]
'''El Arenosillo test Centre''' (CEDEA) is the name of a [[rocket launch site]] for [[suborbital]] [[rocket]]s for [[atmospheric sounding]]s, located near [[Mazagón]] in [[Spain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.inta.es/grandesinstalaciones.aspx?Id=2&SubId=11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825213952/http://www.inta.es/grandesInstalaciones.aspx?Id=2&SubId=11 |archivedate=2012-08-25 |df= }}</ref> It is located in the [[provinces of Spain|province]] of [[Huelva (province)|Huelva]] in southern [[Spain]], in the southwestern part of the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of [[Andalucía]].

The first launch of a rocket from El Arenosillo took place October 4, 1966. Up to 1994 a total of 557 rockets were launched from this base, mainly of the [[Skua (rocket)|Skua]] type and in collaboration with other countries.<ref>http://www.astronautix.com/sites/elasillo.htm</ref>

All rockets for atmospheric soundings in Spain are launched from El Arenosillo. In 2015 [[Delft Aerospace Rocket Engineering]] broke the European altitude record for amateur rocketry by launching the Stratos II+ rocket to 21.5 km altitude from El Arenosillo.<ref>http://www.tudelft.nl/nl/actueel/laatste-nieuws/artikel/detail/missie-geslaagd-studentraket-bereikt-215-km-hoogte/</ref>

El Arenosillo is also the location of an autonomous [[astronomical observatory]] of the [[BOOTES]] network [http://bootes.iaa.es/], with two domes and three telescopes.




