{{Multiple issues| {{refimprove|date=April 2008}} {{cleanup|date=July 2011}} {{update|date=July 2011}} }} {{Infobox oil field | name = Makó gas field | image = | caption = | location_map = Hungary | location_map_width = | location_map_text = | coordinates = {{coord|46|12|54|N|20|28|32|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = [[Hungary]] | region = | location = | block = | offonshore = Onshore | operators = | partner = Falcon Oil & Gas | contractors = | discovery = 1960s | start_development = | start_production = 2006 | peak_year = | abandonment = | peak_of_production_oil_bbl/d = | peak_of_production_oil_tpy = | peak_of_production_gas_mmcuft/d = | peak_of_production_gas_mmscm/d = | peak_of_production_gas_bcm/y = | oil_production_bbl/d = | oil_production_tpy = | production_year_oil = | production_gas_mmcuft/d = | production_gas_mmscm/d = | production_gas_bcm/y = 1 | production_year_gas = | est_oil_bbl = | est_oil_t = | recover_oil_bbl = | recover_oil_t = | est_gas_bft = | est_gas_bcm = | recover_gas_bft = | recover_gas_bcm = 1550 | formations = }} The '''Makó gas field''' ('''Makó Trough Pannonian Basin Gas Accumulation''') is a large [[natural gas field]] next to [[Makó]], in southeastern [[Hungary]].
Since the 1960s it was well known that a large gas field existed next to Makó. The disadvantages are the depth of the gas deposit at about {{convert|5000|m}}, and the large [[Geothermal (geology)|thermal increase]] with depth in Hungary (about {{convert|20|m}} per degree Celsius compared to a world-average {{convert|50|m}} per degree Celsius).{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}
In 2005, Canada's Falcon Oil & Gas bought the extraction rights from the Hungarian state for 40 years. It started test extractions in 2006 with {{convert|327|oilbbl}} of [[light crude oil]] and {{convert|110000|m3}} of [[natural gas]] daily. In 2008 April, [[ExxonMobil]] signed a contract of cooperation of the extraction with US$75&nbsp;million, and in case of successful co-work with additional $150million. In February 2010, ExxonMobil gave up the project due to the high costs of possible extraction.<ref>{{cite web|author=MTI / hvg.hu |url=http://m.hvg.hu/gazdasag/20100222_makoiarok_gazkutatas_exxon_mobil_mol |title=hvg.hu |publisher=M.hvg.hu |date= |accessdate=2013-10-12}}</ref>
At the 90% probability rate, Makó had certified recoverable resources of over {{convert|600|e9m3|abbr=off}} of natural gas, according to a report by the Scotia Group, prepared for the field's exploration concession holder, the Canada-based Falcon Oil and Gas. Later estimates rose to about {{convert|1550|e9m3|abbr=off}} of natural gas.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}
